ative practice to health-policy considerations and parenting. Merging theory and practice with personal narratives and public policy, the book develops a new framework for approaching Black women's wellness in order to provide tangible solutions. The collection reflects feminist praxis and defines womanist peace in terms that reject both "superwoman" stereotypes and "victim" caricatures. Also included for health professionals are concrete recommendations for understanding and treating Black women."…this book speaks not only to Black women but also educates a broader audience of policymakers and therapists about the complex and multilayered realities that we must navigate and the protests we must mount on our journey to find inner peace and optimal health." — from the Foreword by Linda Goler BlountFor access to an online resource created by the editors, visit: Black Women's Mental Health @ http://www.bwmentalhealth.net/  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican American womenxMental health. 0aMental health. 0aWomenxMental health. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPsychology : Mental Health. 4aPsychology : Psychology of Women. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Mental Health.2bisacsh1 aAfejuku, Alero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Kami J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Kanika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Kanika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlount, Linda Goler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradford, Joy Harden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Diane R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.